      definition: {
        elementary: 'When you think things are only good or only bad, with nothing in between. Like everything is either the best or the worst.',
        middle: 'Seeing situations in only two categories instead of on a spectrum. There is no middle ground, no shades of gray, only extremes.',
        high: 'Viewing situations, people, or yourself in absolute, binary terms (perfect/failure, success/disaster) with no acknowledgment of nuance or gradient.'
      },
      examples: {
        elementary: ['I got one answer wrong so I failed the whole test.', 'My friend didn\'t want to play today, she hates me now.', 'I missed the soccer ball, I\'m the worst player ever.', 'I forgot my homework once, I\'m a bad student.'],
        middle: ['If I don\'t get an A, I might as well have failed.', 'She didn\'t invite me, no one in this school likes me.', 'I messed up my speech, the whole presentation was a disaster.', 'If I can\'t do it perfectly, I won\'t do it at all.'],
        high: ['If I don\'t get into my top college, my entire future is ruined.', 'One bad grade and my GPA is destroyed forever.', 'If this relationship doesn\'t work, I\'ll never find love.', 'I either crush this audition or my dream is over.']
      },
      antidote: 'Look for the middle ground and rate the situation on a scale instead of using extreme labels.',
      antidoteSteps: [
        'Notice the extreme words you used (always, never, totally, completely, ruined).',
        'Ask: on a scale of 0 to 100, how bad is this really?',
        'List what actually went well alongside what did not.',
        'Rewrite the thought using a percentage or a range (e.g., "I did 70% of this well").',
        'Rate how strongly you believe the new thought from 0 to 100.'
      ],
      challengeQuestions: [
        'Is this really 100% true, or somewhere in between?',
        'What is a middle-ground way to describe what happened?',
        'If I rated this on a 0 to 10 scale, what number would it actually be?',
        'Would I describe a friend\'s situation this extremely?',
        'What parts of this went okay or even well?'
      ],
      research: 'Identified by Beck (1976) as a core cognitive distortion in depression; expanded by Burns (1980) in Feeling Good.'
